.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Inject from stdin using echo
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
echo \-n \[dq]myrandomdata\[dq] | tpm2_stirrandom
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Inject 64 bytes from stdin using a file
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
dd if=/dev/urandom bs=1 count=64 > myrandom.bin

tpm2_stirrandom < ./myrandom.bin
\f[R]
.fi
.SS Inject bytes from a file and reading up to 128 bytes
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
dd if=/dev/urandom of=./myrandom.bin bs=1 count=42

tpm2_stirrandom ./myrandom.bin
\f[R]
.fi
.SH NOTES
.PP
Please be aware that even if the \[lq]additional information\[rq] added
by \f[B]tpm2_stirrandom\f[R](1) can be entropy gathered from other DRBG
sources, the TPM has no way of determining if the value has any entropy
or not.
As a consequence, it will just be considered as \[lq]additional
input\[rq].
.PP
The \[lq]additional input\[rq] is as defined in NIST
SP800\-90A (https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-90.pdf)
